<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
This year's budget proposal for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration includes a small but historic item that deserves your full support: the $125 million request to initiate development of nuclear electric propulsion (NEP), in which a spacecraft's ion drive would be powered not by huge solar panels but by a miniature nuclear reactor. A solar-powered ion drive such as on the highly successful &lt;i<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/grin.gif ALT=">D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> eep Space 1&lt;/i&gt; probe becomes hopelessly inefficient partway through the Asteroid Belt - but a nuclear-powered one could continue firing continuously anywhere in the Solar System. <br>
<br>
This would not only allow quick sprints to even the most distant planets; it would then allow the craft to easily brake itself into orbit around its destination planet without the need for huge fuel tanks - and, even after all that, it would have 20 km/second or so of maneuvering capability left, allowing it to cruise virtually anywhere within the planet's system of moons, and repeatedly enter or leave orbit around the moons themselves. <br>
<br>
But NEP - quite apart from the fact that its development would take about a billion dollars by itself - has, of course, the huge disadvantage that people do not look fondly on putting large amounts of radioactive material into orbit where it could sooner or later sprinkle down on their heads. <br>
<br>
The relatively small amounts of plutonium-238 contained in the radioactive thermoelectric generators (RTG's) of present-day outer planet probes such as &lt;i&gt;Cassini&lt;/i&gt; produce more than enough unease already, despite NASA's repeated attempts to assure everyone that there is no significant danger of a launch accident or accidental reentry scattering powdered plutonium into the atmosphere. <br>
<br>
YET, an NEP craft's reactor could be made much safer than the current-day RTG's. It could be fueled with uranium-235 - which is more expensive than plutonium, but fully a thousand times less radioactive when not piled up into a critical mass. And such a craft could be launched, unfueled, into a high Earth orbit from which it would virtually never reenter, and only then be loaded with uranium fuel carried in two or more separate unmanned satellites that would automatically dock with it before it lit up its engines and left Earth. <br>
<br>
Extremists and pressure groups will naturally object to any application of nuclear power. These groups have a political and cultural agenda that goes far beyond any authentic concern about the safety of nuclear energy, as their almost unanimous opposition to the war against terrorism has dramatically demonstrated. These groups incessantly presume to speak for &quot;the people&quot;. They do not, you do. We cannot allow the potential of nuclear space propulsion to slip through our fingers. Please support this budget request.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/upriusguy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>priusguy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/02 1:03:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Argh!</span><hr size=1> Somehow the HTML codes failed to execute. Anyway, I put &quot;Deep Space 1&quot; and &quot;Cassini&quot; in italics in the letter.<br>
<br>
Projectorion:<br>
<br>
I think your personal attacks against the &quot;no-nukes!&quot; types are counterproductive. Not that Bruce Gagnon and Michio Kaku do not deserve it, but the only way to defeat them is by educating the many many people who know nothing about nuclear power and radiation, and hence listen to those who purport to &quot;protect them from evil&quot;. You do it by maintaining a rational tone however much you are tempted otherwise. Name-calling only convinces the uneducated that you are just what Gagnon claims you are. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 230<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/02 2:37:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/homer.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Letter...</span><hr size=1> Maybe we should add your version as an alternative letter to the link<br>
from the main page?<br>
<br>
Do I have your permission? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/upriusguy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>priusguy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/02 5:10:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/homer.gif" align=absmiddle>  Link to a letter</span><hr size=1> You probably should not. Parts of this letter were lifted verbatim from an article by Bruce Moomaw in SpaceDaily.com. I doubt he minds the usage, but no need to give any excuse to the people who would shut this website down if they could. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/02 8:20:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Tailored letters</span><hr size=1> It is an excellent idea to tailor the letters to a particular Representative since we want to be able to address the entire spectrum of political opinion here. The original was written to Congressman Larry Combest of Texas, a noted conservative and a staunch supporter of nuclear energy in all its forms, including nuclear weapons. The same is true of the two Texas senators. Orion is probably not the best example to use with many other Representatives or Senators. <br>
A small number of personalized letters have much greater impact than any number of organizational form letters in any case. We can't compete in numbers, but we can get our point across in ways that will be noticed.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 471<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/18/02 9:11:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Tailored letters</span><hr size=1> The points which need to be covered are that nuclear power is now out of it's infancy. We now understand it well enough to use it safely. That their reactions should not be based on lingering fears from early accidents which were actually few, or on poorly operated Russian plants either. With sensible management nuclear power is safe and politicians should lead the way in embracing this huge technologically progressive stride forward. Not cling to Hollywood urban myths and try to stifle it. We must have a nuclear space age. Just as we had to have a chemical rocket age. Only one frontier remains and it is not without risk. Chemical rockets have done all they can. Nuclear power deserves a chance. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
